this is a mysql-like memory database, which supports some basic sql queries, like select, insert, update and delete.
I wrote this small project to practise.

the persistence is WAL plus SNAPSHOT, very basic, but enough for this toy database.

I will continue improve this mysql-like memory database project, for example, to support the index, and 

you could use jbang to check the SqlTest.java file, it has the basic usage of this database.


Critical bugs:

5. 
SELECT lowercases the entire query — Select.java:15 calls toLowerCase() on the full SQL string. Column values like Alice become alice, but INSERT stores original case. Queries like WHERE name = Alice will never match.
6. 
Inconsistent case handling in Database.exec() — CREATE uses query.toLowerCase().startsWith(...), but INSERT, SELECT, UPDATE use query.startsWith(...) with lowercase constants. This works only if the query is already lowercase — mixed case will silently fail.
Design improvements:
7. SQL parsing is fragile — Heavy reliance on split() and contains() breaks on values containing keywords like "from", "where", "and". No support for quoted strings. Consider a real parser or at least tokenization with quote awareness.
8. No type system — All values are stored as String. No INT/DATE/VARCHAR distinction. The shop fixture writes Alice without quotes (invalid SQL), so the parser can't distinguish identifiers from string literals.
9. WHERE only supports AND — Comment says "will support or later" but the logic in filterByWhere hardcodes AND with early-exit on false. Need a composite expression tree for full WHERE support.
10. Snapshot serialization is fragile — Java serialization on List<List<String>> will break if the class evolves. Use JSON or a defined binary format.
Missing features:
- 
No primary keys or row identity (can't distinguish duplicate rows, can't implement DELETE or point updates)
- 
No index support (hash index is mentioned in test comments but absent)
- 
shop log file uses Alice without quotes — causing ambiguity with column names


For range query support (<, >, <=, >=), a B+Tree would be the natural choice — it's what real MySQL InnoDB uses.
Conceptually for an in-memory version:
- 
Internal nodes route searches, leaf nodes contain sorted key + list of row references in sorted order.
- 
Leaf nodes are linked for efficient range scans — once you find the start of a range, you just walk the linked list.
- 
On INSERT, insert the key into the B+Tree (find the right leaf, insert sorted, split if full).
- 
On UPDATE/DELETE, remove and re-insert the key.
- 
Self-balancing, O(log n) for point lookups and range queries.
A simpler alternative with the same property: skip list. Easier to implement, probabilistic O(log n), and also supports efficient range scans — just find the start node then follow pointers.